UPDATE public.blog_posts SET
  blocks_es = '[{"id":"6e40c9d4-f2f5-40cc-a025-8fadf9655325","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>TL;DR — Lo esencial en 3 puntos</strong><br/>Vender horas tiene un techo natural: solo hay tantas horas al día por persona. Las agencias que ganan margen sin inflar plantilla suelen haber cambiado **qué venden**, no cuánto sudan.<br/>El **margen bruto por proyecto** es la métrica que separa quien factura mucho de quien se queda con dinero. Hacer el ejercicio con tus últimos diez proyectos suele ser incómodo y útil a la vez.<br/>El scope creep no es solo «clientes difíciles»: es falta de contenedor. Un protocolo de tres pasos —registrar, cuantificar, comunicar— se puede poner en marcha sin esperar al próximo trimestre."},{"id":"358643f7-b218-46b6-904e-87057f51efcc","type":"paragraph","html":"Si ya leíste por qué <LocaleLink>estar ocupado no significa ser rentable</LocaleLink>, el siguiente paso es incómodo de verdad: mirar los proyectos uno a uno y preguntarte si el precio tenía sentido con el coste real —no con el coste que te gustaría creer."},{"id":"88ebea5d-8824-4a81-87ab-40340d2bcd3f","type":"paragraph","html":"Aquí vas a encontrar <strong>modelos de pricing con pros y contras</strong>, un cálculo de margen que puedes llevar a una hoja sin filosofía, un protocolo de alcance que evita trabajar gratis por omisión, y una forma de enmarcar el trabajo en ciclos cortos para que el tiempo deje de ser un río sin orillas."},{"id":"8549d51c-3f6f-4987-9e5a-85dccd44a5f8","type":"toc"},{"id":"df859e24-18c4-43cc-9105-21b73f6dc46d","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Por qué vender horas tiene un techo y cómo romperlo","anchorId":"techo-horas"},{"id":"00c2548f-dd6c-498f-afde-9948215f7110","type":"paragraph","html":"Cuando el precio está atado al tiempo, <strong>la eficiencia se penaliza sola</strong>: si el equipo hace en dos horas lo que antes tardaba cuatro, cobras la mitad por el mismo resultado. Ese incentivo perverso explica por qué muchas agencias se quedan atrapadas en una carrera de más horas o más cabezas."},{"id":"55dea515-246b-4597-9616-8fb1fb223238","type":"paragraph","html":"Te lo encontrarás en el “buenas noticias”: el equipo mejora el proceso, reduce tiempos, y aun así el mes no cumple porque la facturación también baja. Es el techo hablando claro, no tú perdiendo motivación."},{"id":"0e5cb9b1-10ce-4823-a313-82036139721e","type":"paragraph","html":"Además, el precio hora es fácil de comparar entre proveedores; el precio atado a un <strong>resultado con alcance definido</strong> no lo es tanto. Eso cambia la conversación —si tienes autoridad y datos para sostenerla."},{"id":"86221efa-3475-4771-94c2-a4e4c4c91dc1","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Pricing basado en valor: cuándo es realista"},{"id":"9e8aa079-ad82-4225-b0b9-00ce0a832c99","type":"paragraph","html":"Desvincular el precio del tiempo y acercarlo al impacto para el cliente puede subir margen sin subir headcount. Funciona si tienes datos de resultados previos y track record demostrado; sin eso, es una negociación difícil de ganar. En el fondo, es vender la solución al problema, no el tiempo que tardas en teclearla."},{"id":"beeb5eb6-0006-49d9-8c69-6e00acc65a16","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Modelos de pricing: pros, contras y el modelo híbrido","anchorId":"modelos-pricing"},{"id":"d39f994f-9c8d-46bc-931f-1fe146799f58","type":"paragraph","html":"No hay un modelo perfecto, pero sí hay modelos que atraen los problemas que no quieres. La cicatriz típica es el fee que parece estable hasta que el cliente mete “un favorcito” cada tres días y el margen desaparece."},{"id":"e80b7c52-5b35-494f-b1a9-e9d0784a60ef","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Precio por hora / Time & Materials"},{"id":"04afabd7-67ad-46d4-bc6e-b9d2b0b1c8ac","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Seguridad de cobro por cada minuto invertido."},{"id":"58b68405-a1b6-43aa-aafa-2551a0be40a3","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> Penaliza la eficiencia y dificulta la previsión de ingresos para el cliente."},{"id":"50fcd2fe-79a4-476f-8824-b0607a623f02","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Precio fijo por proyecto"},{"id":"96c40ec0-3e06-48dc-963d-f32f1cd5c793","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Claridad total para el cliente y premio a la rapidez si tienes procesos finos."},{"id":"5da48b93-3fc5-4f81-b4dc-d3662c88b1c3","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> Todo el riesgo de desviación (scope creep) lo asume la agencia."},{"id":"f9331312-bda0-4c55-bfc4-8c3fd2d80dbe","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Retainer mensual (Fee recurrente)"},{"id":"f6045fd2-3ff8-4d8b-bdc5-e67ad14b6868","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Predecibilidad de caja y relación a largo plazo."},{"id":"182b18d7-22c7-40c7-9eb5-d27acdce9135","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> Tendencia a la «comodidad» del cliente (pide de más) y a la «relajación» de la agencia (mide de menos)."},{"id":"47543c85-6e4b-432a-959d-9cab86150df4","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"El modelo híbrido: lo mejor de dos mundos"},{"id":"29d69b51-e1a7-462a-a3cb-66de559ae81e","type":"paragraph","html":"La mayoría de agencias rentables usan un mix: un **fee base** para el mantenimiento y **proyectos cerrados** para iniciativas nuevas o picos de trabajo. Eso asegura el suelo de ingresos y protege el margen de los extras."},{"id":"df0cf941-e474-4bd4-a592-e7f9403ec023","type":"visualRef","visualId":"OcupacionVsRentabilidadChart"},{"id":"22ca7833-a0d9-4784-9c89-cfe7ad123b8e","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Cómo calcular el margen bruto real por proyecto","anchorId":"calcular-rentabilidad"},{"id":"833abaa7-c749-486b-a026-3a2c3e508e81","type":"paragraph","html":"Ojo: el margen neto de la agencia (lo que queda después de pagar oficina, software y administración) importa, pero la batalla se gana en el **margen bruto por proyecto**. Si el proyecto por sí solo no deja aire, la agencia no tiene futuro."},{"id":"ad2141ad-3cc0-4180-9ade-4e3e8a93a90d","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"<strong>La fórmula básica</strong><br/>(Ingresos del proyecto − Costes directos) / Ingresos × 100<br/>Donde el **coste directo** incluye las horas del equipo (a coste cargado: sueldo + seguridad social + extras), freelancers y herramientas específicas del encargo."},{"id":"cac86a3e-7087-40df-8523-6d43fd2b89a8","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>Referencias rápidas</strong><br/>Saludable: > 50-60%. Tienes aire para cubrir overhead y crecer.<br/>Peligro: < 35-40%. El proyecto apenas paga su propia ejecución; estás subvencionando al cliente con tu estructura."},{"id":"d79811b4-349e-4a9c-a8fd-b9c81a790647","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. El protocolo de alcance en tres pasos","anchorId":"scope-protocolo"},{"id":"6efe5554-73eb-4722-bcad-2fbfcbe2b1b8","type":"paragraph","html":"El scope creep (alcance que crece) destruye más márgenes que la mala suerte. No se frena con enfados, se frena con un contenedor. La cicatriz es el “pero si esto ya estaba” que te sueltan cuando intentas cobrar la quinta revisión."},{"id":"3e274d0a-5f53-4bb1-a6ba-68a1fbc0ac6a","type":"list","ordered":true,"items":["<strong>Registrar:</strong> nada se acepta por chat o de palabra sin que entre en el sistema de gestión.","<strong>Cuantificar:</strong> ¿cuántas horas son? ¿qué impacto tiene en la fecha final?","<strong>Comunicar:</strong> «Esto está fuera del alcance original. Podemos hacerlo sumando X al presupuesto o quitando Y de la cola actual». El cliente elige, tú no pierdes."]},{"id":"66a0cd5a-cf70-4684-a09b-2b8f187c4fad","type":"visualRef","visualId":"ScopeProtocoloInfographic"},{"id":"ea9586f0-1b25-431d-8a43-806abc92e1f0","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. El modelo de sprint: de fee infinito a ciclos cerrados","anchorId":"modelo-sprint"},{"id":"df739eb0-9319-4e6d-8ba9-754a9d894edf","type":"paragraph","html":"Trabajar por sprints (ciclos de 1 o 2 semanas) ayuda a que el tiempo no se dilate. En lugar de un proyecto de tres meses que se deforma, tienes 6 entregas de dos semanas con objetivos inamovibles. Lo notas cuando el equipo deja de preguntar “¿cuándo acaba esto?” y empieza a decir “esto entra en el sprint que viene”."},{"id":"1d7bf0aa-1654-4132-9106-b366019543c2","type":"paragraph","html":"Si quieres conectar el calendario con la capacidad real de tu gente, la <LocaleLink>planificación de recursos del equipo</LocaleLink> cuenta cómo unir fechas y cabezas sin que nadie explote. Y para saber si el ritmo es el adecuado, el <LocaleLink>pacing de proyectos</LocaleLink> te da el pulso en tiempo real."},{"id":"a42cbd10-3b2a-435b-83e9-c7691f9eae39","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Preguntas frecuentes","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"ce71a85b-470c-4d95-b18d-726cbc3bc6cc","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"¿Qué margen bruto debe tener una agencia de marketing?","a":"La referencia habitual en agencias de servicios sitúa un margen bruto saludable por encima del 50% por proyecto. Por debajo del 40%, el proyecto difícilmente cubre costes indirectos y overhead de forma sostenible. El margen bruto se calcula como (ingresos – coste directo) / ingresos × 100."},{"q":"¿Cómo se cobra el trabajo extra fuera del alcance en una agencia?","a":"El proceso más efectivo tiene tres pasos: registrar la solicitud en el momento, estimar el tiempo antes de aceptar, y comunicar el impacto al cliente antes de ejecutar. La pregunta que cambia la conversación es: ''¿Lo añadimos ajustando el presupuesto, o lo dejamos para el próximo sprint?''"},{"q":"¿Qué es mejor para una agencia: retainer o precio por proyecto?","a":"Depende del tipo de servicio. El retainer funciona mejor para servicios continuos y bien definidos (SEO, gestión de redes). El precio por proyecto funciona mejor para trabajos puntuales con scope variable. Los datos del sector apuntan a que el modelo híbrido — 60-70% retainer, 30-40% proyectos — ofrece el mejor equilibrio entre predecibilidad y flexibilidad."},{"q":"¿Cómo puedo saber qué proyectos son más rentables en mi agencia?","a":"Calculando el margen bruto real de tus últimos 10-15 proyectos: (ingresos – coste directo total) / ingresos × 100. El patrón que emerge casi siempre es el mismo: 2-3 tipos de proyecto concentran el 80% del margen. Esa información es la base de cualquier decisión estratégica de portfolio de servicios."},{"q":"¿Qué es el pricing basado en valor y cuándo aplicarlo?","a":"Es un modelo en el que el precio se fija en función del valor que el trabajo genera para el cliente, no del tiempo invertido. Tiene sentido cuando la agencia tiene datos de resultados previos y track record demostrable que justifique el precio. Sin esas condiciones, es difícil de sostener en la negociación."}]},{"id":"1695f13f-046b-4dbf-ab19-614f264e5262","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Empieza a medir hoy","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"406071ae-b867-4a42-a723-5cc31ae0bce4","type":"paragraph","html":"No esperes a que el Excel te avise de que no queda margen. La rentabilidad se construye decisión a decisión."},{"id":"502a266d-fad9-4757-b8df-7e80151fc2b9","type":"cta","text":"Ver herramientas de rentabilidad","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"2a00ddae-0d5b-4586-88ba-1cb43850c9c5","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  blocks_en = '[{"id":"75a8a30c-69fd-4d7c-9df1-093412013a9e","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>TL;DR — The essentials in 3 points</strong><br/>Selling hours has a natural ceiling: there are only so many hours in a day per person. Agencies that gain margin without inflating headcount have usually changed **what they sell**, not how much they sweat.<br/>The **gross margin per project** is the metric that separates those who bill a lot from those who keep the money. Doing this exercise with your last ten projects is usually both uncomfortable and useful.<br/>Scope creep isn''t just ''difficult clients'': it''s a lack of a container. A three-step protocol —record, quantify, communicate— can be set in motion without waiting for the next quarter."},{"id":"fcb84a2a-a634-4e90-94f8-cec13e3b8b6a","type":"paragraph","html":"If you''ve already read why <LocaleLink>being busy doesn''t mean being profitable</LocaleLink>, the next step is truly uncomfortable: looking at projects one by one and asking yourself if the price made sense with the real cost —not with the cost you''d like to believe."},{"id":"df3beb95-0be6-4ff3-b787-c7cc135090e8","type":"paragraph","html":"Here you will find <strong>pricing models with pros and cons</strong>, a margin calculation you can take to a spreadsheet without philosophy, a scope protocol that avoids working for free by omission, and a way to frame work in short cycles so that time stops being a river without banks."},{"id":"9c1c7c8e-0340-4e5e-8fe7-97b64d706211","type":"toc"},{"id":"f71af4da-2595-414b-86ba-0fc5163e4485","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Why selling hours has a ceiling and how to break it","anchorId":"techo-horas"},{"id":"0b82f1bb-7bc2-406f-99b5-cda6fb44d5f2","type":"paragraph","html":"When price is tied to time, <strong>efficiency penalizes itself</strong>: if the team does in two hours what used to take four, you bill half for the same result. This perverse incentive explains why many agencies get trapped in a race for more hours or more heads."},{"id":"06cabf36-aeb5-4325-b0e4-ed553d4940f3","type":"paragraph","html":"You''ll find it in the ''good news'': the team improves the process, reduces times, and yet the month doesn''t deliver because billing also drops. It''s the ceiling speaking clearly, not you losing motivation."},{"id":"34ce56ad-3e9b-471b-ba8f-46755ed5d920","type":"paragraph","html":"In addition, the hourly price is easy to compare between providers; the price tied to a <strong>result with defined scope</strong> is not so much. That changes the conversation —if you have the authority and data to sustain it."},{"id":"e48c5989-6930-45bc-bd8a-fe80cec7aa33","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Value-based pricing: when it''s realistic"},{"id":"ce8bbdc6-08cb-4783-8974-863725133f04","type":"paragraph","html":"Decoupling price from time and moving it closer to the impact for the client can increase margin without increasing headcount. It works if you have data from previous results and a proven track record; without that, it''s a difficult negotiation to win. In the end, it''s about selling the solution to the problem, not the time it takes to type it up."},{"id":"27cf002a-3354-4135-9601-17ff355de76d","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Pricing models: pros, cons, and the hybrid model","anchorId":"modelos-pricing"},{"id":"36b0f199-d20d-4751-86aa-bcd9ea6670f1","type":"paragraph","html":"There is no perfect model, but there are models that attract the problems you don''t want. The typical scar is the fee that seems stable until the client asks for ''a little favor'' every three days and the margin disappears."},{"id":"75b7d334-7e72-47ee-a4db-5f39a3eeb8bd","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hourly price / Time & Materials"},{"id":"9d45ce6f-71ff-41b4-bcd3-60a2ed2bd2b4","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Certainty of collection for every minute invested."},{"id":"252f6155-ed8b-43f6-8403-705c48bcd688","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> Penalizes efficiency and makes it difficult for the client to forecast income."},{"id":"099da42c-e91c-4d42-bc0b-c1c4d453a804","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Fixed price per project"},{"id":"a74578ba-ba95-4e41-b43c-5106936e5d56","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Total clarity for the client and a reward for speed if you have smooth processes."},{"id":"eb7c5bb3-19cc-4dbd-9288-a524f4713d82","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> The agency assumes all the risk of deviation (scope creep)."},{"id":"4461fd7c-ed02-4da9-8d04-718275276bfa","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Monthly retainer (Recurring Fee)"},{"id":"b12c9e64-33b3-4455-8b37-ab6bfa76bd03","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Cash flow predictability and long-term relationship."},{"id":"6b890f86-8cd0-4971-92ab-fd970ca1e900","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> Tendency towards client ''comfort'' (asking for too much) and agency ''relaxation'' (measuring too little)."},{"id":"631f6787-62a7-4dff-8e32-3986e2809980","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The hybrid model: the best of both worlds"},{"id":"05ce5995-e997-40cc-b961-f2522cba2bac","type":"paragraph","html":"Most profitable agencies use a mix: a **base fee** for maintenance and **fixed projects** for new initiatives or peaks in work. This ensures an income floor and protects the margin from extras."},{"id":"4002eec1-dc6c-412f-a45a-06b6ee5bb7fb","type":"visualRef","visualId":"OcupacionVsRentabilidadChart"},{"id":"631157b1-2f06-42d0-ba24-b304ad4be733","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. How to calculate real gross margin per project","anchorId":"calcular-rentabilidad"},{"id":"551539f2-bec9-44ac-aa4a-3f3476327e3c","type":"paragraph","html":"Note: the agency''s net margin (what''s left after paying for office, software, and administration) matters, but the battle is won in the **gross margin per project**. If the project alone doesn''t leave room to breathe, the agency has no future."},{"id":"34a86adf-1288-4e2e-82d3-0bb794cb960b","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"<strong>The basic formula</strong><br/>(Project Revenue − Direct Costs) / Revenue × 100<br/>Where **direct cost** includes team hours (at fully loaded cost: salary + social security + extras), freelancers, and specific tools for the assignment."},{"id":"b7dcd919-5147-4327-97c8-055db50a2737","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>Quick references</strong><br/>Healthy: > 50-60%. You have room to cover overhead and grow.<br/>Danger: < 35-40%. The project barely pays for its own execution; you are subsidizing the client with your structure."},{"id":"99cad709-e026-4c35-947a-fe8c89377907","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. The three-step scope protocol","anchorId":"scope-protocolo"},{"id":"c9adf11c-036a-4461-9f36-48018f1ecbf9","type":"paragraph","html":"Scope creep (growing scope) destroys more margins than bad luck. It isn''t stopped with anger; it''s stopped with a container. The scar is the ''but this was already in'' that they tell you when you try to bill for the fifth revision."},{"id":"6c883e64-810e-4bea-9bc8-4a1f53378f9c","type":"list","ordered":true,"items":["<strong>Record:</strong> nothing is accepted by chat or word of mouth without it entering the management system.","<strong>Quantify:</strong> how many hours is it? what impact does it have on the final date?","<strong>Communicate:</strong> ''This is outside the original scope. We can do it by adding X to the budget or removing Y from the current queue.'' The client chooses, you don''t lose."]},{"id":"a9f10123-a852-4cfb-95e1-380f4c1fde95","type":"visualRef","visualId":"ScopeProtocoloInfographic"},{"id":"67cf7b53-efee-440d-8233-46a66db0d3b5","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. The sprint model: from infinite fee to closed cycles","anchorId":"modelo-sprint"},{"id":"53d21387-65ff-4c97-b1cd-41a8e9b6ae9c","type":"paragraph","html":"Working by sprints (1 or 2 week cycles) helps time not to dilate. Instead of a three-month project that gets deformed, you have six two-week deliveries with fixed objectives. You notice it when the team stops asking ''when does this end?'' and starts saying ''this goes into the next sprint''."},{"id":"5da1017e-497c-4136-8599-eddd1b88f0d6","type":"paragraph","html":"If you want to connect the calendar with your people''s real capacity, the <LocaleLink>team resource planning</LocaleLink> tells you how to join dates and heads without anyone exploding. And to know if the pace is right, <LocaleLink>project pacing</LocaleLink> gives you the pulse in real time."},{"id":"d84e103f-803d-42d4-99bd-1fa4a05e4024","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Frequently Asked Questions","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"cc726461-ac40-4519-9884-fb2b041d5def","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"What gross margin should a marketing agency have?","a":"The standard reference in service agencies sets a healthy gross margin above 50% per project. Below 40%, the project hardly covers indirect costs and overhead sustainably. Gross margin is calculated as (revenue – direct cost) / revenue × 100."},{"q":"How is extra work outside the scope charged in an agency?","a":"The most effective process has three steps: log the request at the moment, estimate the time before accepting, and communicate the impact to the client before executing. The question that changes the conversation is: ''Do we add it by adjusting the budget, or leave it for the next sprint?''"},{"q":"What is better for an agency: retainer or price per project?","a":"It depends on the type of service. Retainers work best for continuous and well-defined services (SEO, social media management). Per-project pricing works better for one-off jobs with variable scope. Industry data suggests that the hybrid model — 60-70% retainer, 30-40% projects — offers the best balance between predictability and flexibility."},{"q":"How can I know which projects are most profitable in my agency?","a":"By calculating the real gross margin of your last 10-15 projects: (revenue – total direct cost) / revenue × 100. The pattern that almost always emerges is the same: 2-3 types of projects concentrate 80% of the margin. This information is the basis for any strategic service portfolio decision."},{"q":"What is value-based pricing and when to apply it?","a":"It is a model where the price is set based on the value the work generates for the client, not the time invested. It makes sense when the agency has data from previous results and a demonstrable track record that justifies the price. Without those conditions, it is difficult to sustain in negotiation."}]},{"id":"2c1a8c01-3b74-49a2-a9a8-179b775fccf5","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Start measuring today","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"fe3ba498-86ea-416a-943f-d3f00d81cb0b","type":"paragraph","html":"Don''t wait for Excel to warn you that there''s no margin left. Profitability is built decision by decision."},{"id":"3b43bbcf-9727-4d54-82e1-71c151bd9f40","type":"cta","text":"View profitability tools","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"b89921f4-683e-4704-a506-d7695ea3ef32","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  json_ld_es = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Cómo medir la rentabilidad real por proyecto en tu agencia (y dejar de vender horas)","description":"De vender tiempo a vender valor: cómo calcular el margen real por proyecto, comparar modelos de pricing y proteger tus beneficios frente al scope creep.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-26","inLanguage":"es","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/blog/como-medir-rentabilidad-proyecto-agencia-dejar-vender-horas"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué margen bruto debe tener una agencia de marketing?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"La referencia habitual en agencias de servicios sitúa un margen bruto saludable por encima del 50% por proyecto. Por debajo del 40%, el proyecto difícilmente cubre costes indirectos y overhead de forma sostenible. El margen bruto se calcula como (ingresos – coste directo) / ingresos × 100."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cómo se cobra el trabajo extra fuera del alcance en una agencia?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"El proceso más efectivo tiene tres pasos: registrar la solicitud en el momento, estimar el tiempo antes de aceptar, y comunicar el impacto al cliente antes de ejecutar. La pregunta que cambia la conversación es: ''¿Lo añadimos ajustando el presupuesto, o lo dejamos para el próximo sprint?''"}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué es mejor para una agencia: retainer o precio por proyecto?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Depende del tipo de servicio. El retainer funciona mejor para servicios continuos y bien definidos (SEO, gestión de redes). El precio por proyecto funciona mejor para trabajos puntuales con scope variable. Los datos del sector apuntan a que el modelo híbrido — 60-70% retainer, 30-40% proyectos — ofrece el mejor equilibrio entre predecibilidad y flexibilidad."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cómo puedo saber qué proyectos son más rentables en mi agencia?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Calculando el margen bruto real de tus últimos 10-15 proyectos: (ingresos – coste directo total) / ingresos × 100. El patrón que emerge casi siempre es el mismo: 2-3 tipos de proyecto concentran el 80% del margen. Esa información es la base de cualquier decisión estratégica de portfolio de servicios."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué es el pricing basado en valor y cuándo aplicarlo?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Es un modelo en el que el precio se fija en función del valor que el trabajo genera para el cliente, no del tiempo invertido. Tiene sentido cuando la agencia tiene datos de resultados previos y track record demostrable que justifique el precio. Sin esas condiciones, es difícil de sostener en la negociación."}}]},{"@type":"SoftwareApplication","name":"Taimbox","applicationCategory":"BusinessApplication","description":"Planificador de recursos y tiempo para agencias. Timeboxing, cronograma por horas y reportes de rentabilidad."}]}'::jsonb,
  json_ld_en = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"How to measure the real profitability per project in your agency (and stop selling hours)","description":"From selling time to selling value: how to calculate the real margin per project, compare pricing models and protect your profits against scope creep.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-26","inLanguage":"en","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/en/blog/measure-project-profitability-stop-selling-hours"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What gross margin should a marketing agency have?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The standard reference in service agencies sets a healthy gross margin above 50% per project. Below 40%, the project hardly covers indirect costs and overhead sustainably. Gross margin is calculated as (revenue – direct cost) / revenue × 100."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How is extra work outside the scope charged in an agency?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The most effective process has three steps: log the request at the moment, estimate the time before accepting, and communicate the impact to the client before executing. The question that changes the conversation is: ''Do we add it by adjusting the budget, or leave it for the next sprint?''"}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What is better for an agency: retainer or price per project?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"It depends on the type of service. Retainers work best for continuous and well-defined services (SEO, social media management). Per-project pricing works better for one-off jobs with variable scope. Industry data suggests that the hybrid model — 60-70% retainer, 30-40% projects — offers the best balance between predictability and flexibility."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How can I know which projects are most profitable in my agency?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"By calculating the real gross margin of your last 10-15 projects: (revenue – total direct cost) / revenue × 100. The pattern that almost always emerges is the same: 2-3 types of projects concentrate 80% of the margin. This information is the basis for any strategic service portfolio decision."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What is value-based pricing and when to apply it?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"It is a model where the price is set based on the value the work generates for the client, not the time invested. It makes sense when the agency has data from previous results and a demonstrable track record that justifies the price. Without those conditions, it is difficult to sustain in negotiation."}}]},{"@type":"SoftwareApplication","name":"Taimbox","applicationCategory":"BusinessApplication","description":"Agency resource and time planner. Timeboxing, hourly schedule, and profitability reports."}]}'::jsonb
